ira/rest/api/2/user?username=pvary","name":"pvary","key":"pvary","avatarUrls":{"48x48":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?avatarId=10452","24x24":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=small&avatarId=10452","16x16":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=xsmall&avatarId=10452","32x32":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=medium&avatarId=10452"},"displayName":"Peter Vary","active":true,"timeZone":"Europe/Budapest"},"body":"[~xuzq_zander]: \"An external table describes the metadata / schema on external files. External table files can be accessed and managed by processes outside of Hive.[..] Use external tables when files are already present or in remote locations, and the files should remain even if the table is dropped.\" - In Hive we do not change the existing file hierarchy for external tables. When dropped / renamed etc. we keep the original structure. AFAIK the Archive function would move exiting files/directories - not really clear what should we do with the EXTERNAL_TABLE files in this case. So I think that is why the author decided to implement the ARCHIVE function only for managed tables.\r\n\r\nHope this helps,\r\n\r\nPeter","updateAuthor":{"self":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/user?username=pvary","name":"pvary","key":"pvary","avatarUrls":{"48x48":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?avatarId=10452","24x24":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=small&avatarId=10452","16x16":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=xsmall&avatarId=10452","32x32":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=medium&avatarId=10452"},"displayName":"Peter Vary","active":true,"timeZone":"Europe/Budapest"},"created":"2018-05-29T10:24:17.415+0000","updated":"2018-05-29T10:24:17.415+0000"}],"maxResults":1,"total":1,"startAt":0},"votes":{"self":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/issue/HIVE-19722/votes","votes":0,"hasVoted":false},"worklog":{"startAt